Yes. `request-mocking-protocol` lets you match request headers in the request schema. If the headers don’t match, the mock won’t apply (and with unhandled‑request errors enabled, the test fails).

Example in `tests/integration/lead.spec.ts`:

```ts
await mockServerRequest.GET(
  {
    url: "http://anedot.me:3000/public/v3/action_pages/:actionPageSlug",
    query: { account_slug: "demo-org" },
    headers: {
      "x-foo": "bar",
      "x-trace-id": "test-trace-123",
    },
  },
  { body: mockActionPage },
);
```

You can also validate *absence* by setting a header to `null`:

```ts
headers: { "x-experimental": null }
```

If you want, I can wire this into your current tests and, if needed, enable unhandled‑request errors so a header mismatch fails loudly.

